  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">William Lloyd Garrison humorously and seriously describes the water cure. He refers to Francis Jackson&apos;s seeing Niagara Falls and Canada and the Canadian people as &quot;willing to remain in colonial vassalage.&quot; In spirit, Garrison will join the gathering in Lynn to celebrate the first of August, the anniversary of the West Indian Emancipation. Garrison commends his brother-in-law, George William Benson, who lost his position as agent of a factory as a result of being the president of the Anti-Sabbath Convention.</subfield>
